b'-- In short, $FVRR has become one of the dominant platforms in the growing gig economy. With impressive financials, several tailwinds, and a current market cap of $7B, $FVRR could be in the early chapters of a long growth story.'

b'-- Third, $FVRR is moving upstream by offering Fiverr business, which is a service targeted toward larger enterprises. \n\n-- Fourth, $FVRR is offering promoted advertising for sellers, which generates revenue while enabling sellers to increase demand generation.'

b'-- Several factors could drive growth. First, the freelance market is early stages. There are ~57M freelancers in the US, but 95% of transactions happen offline.\n\n-- Second, $FVRR is launching local-language sites (e.g. in Brazil and Mexico) to expand its international footprint.'

b'-- $FVRR also has a stellar 84% gross margin. Combined with the revenue acceleration, $FVRR is rapidly moving toward profitability. It reported a $6.7M loss for the first three quarters of 2020 compared to a $26.1M loss for the same period in 2019.'

b"-- These factors have contributed to impressive financial performance. $FVRR's revenue has grown around 40% y/y since it went public in June 2019. In its last two quarters, $FVRR has reported +80% revenue growth and is guiding for 81% growth next quarter."

b'-- $FVRR recently reported a net promoter score (NPS) of 67 for buyers and 78 for sellers. An NPS is the % of users likely to recommend a service, and a score above 50 is considered very good. With 67 and 78, $FVRR is getting free marketing from both sides of its user base.'

b'-- $FVRR has also built a strong incentive system to encourage quality work: sellers with the best reviews appear at the top of searches, meaning more work and more money. This creates a virtuous cycle: quality sellers attract more customers, which attracts more sellers.'

b"-- By attracting buyers, $FVRR has kick-started a powerful flywheel: more buyers means more sellers come to the platform because that's where the work is. $FVRR sellers apparently welcome the demand as ~70% of them work on 2 or more projects at the same time. https://t.co/qYZggLxrjg"

b'-- Second, $FVRR has successfully built a strong network of buyers. In October 2020, it reported 3.1M buyers on its platform, a 31% y/y increase. Buyer spending increased 20% in that same timeframe.'

b'-- First, $FVRR management estimates the total market opportunity in the US for freelance work is ~$115B. In other words, this is likely not a winner take all market, especially given the opportunities for expansion outside of the US.'

b"-- Although $UPWK's copycatting validates $FVRR's  model, it also increases competition between the two companies. Still, there are at least two reasons why $FVRR may be in the early stages of its growth story."

b"-- $UPWK's system requires more seller involvement with less price certainty for both the buyer and seller. Indeed, apparently recognizing the superiority of $FVRR's model, $UPWK recently launched a menu-based model that mirrors $FVRR's own."

b"-- $FVRR's model also contrasts with $UPWK's original model. Whereas $FVRR has a menu of different service offerings where buyers select a seller, $UPWK uses an auction based system, where buyers submit a project description and sellers actively bid for the work."

b'-- Sellers that post on $FVRR avoid the time and costs associated with traditional freelance marketing (e.g. webpages, social media, etc.).\n\n-- $FVRR also opens up a world-wide market to sellers. A graphic designer in Sweden can perform work for an interior decorator in Arizona.'

b"-- At first glance, $FVRR's take rate appears high relative to other platforms. For example, $UPWK's take rate is ~14%, $ETSY's is 5% (plus 3% if Etsy Payments is used), and $AMZN's is ~25%.\n\n-- However, $FVRR's demand generation for sellers supports the cut that it takes."

b"-- $FVRR has recently become one of the world's largest gig platforms. \n\n-- Its business model is straightforward: $FVRR takes a 20% cut from sellers and a 5% cut from buyers, with a $2 charge for transactions under $40. On balance, its blended take rate is ~27%."

b'Spotlight: $FVRR (1Y +809%)\n\n-- $FVRR operates a two-sided online marketplace for gig workers.
